  <setup>
    <selectFromSequence name="a" from="4" to="7" step="1"/>
    <selectFromSequence name="b" from="4" to="7" step="1" exclude="$a"/>
    <selectFromSequence name="c" from="2" to="5" step="1" exclude="$a $b"/>
    <selectFromSequence name="d" from="2" to="5" step="1" exclude="$a $b $c"/>

    <math name="P">($c*$a+$d)/($a-$b)</math>
    <math name="Q">($c*$b+$d)/($b-$a)</math>    

    <mathList name="PFdecomp">$P/(x-$a) $Q/(x-$b)</mathList>
    <mathList name="PFdecompEntered">$PF1 $PF2</mathList>
    
    <function name="f" symbolic="false" >
      ($c*x+$d)/((x-$a)*(x-$b))
    </function> 

    <function name="F" symbolic="false" >
      $P*ln(abs(x-$a)) + $Q*ln(abs(x-$b))
    </function>   
    
  </setup>

<p>
  Consider the indefinite integral
  <me>
    \int \frac{$c x + $d}{(x-$a)(x-$b)} \, dx
  </me>
  We want to evaluate this integral using the method of partial fractions.
</p>

<p>
  First, find the partial fraction decomposition of the integrand, and enter the result in the following blanks accordingly.
</p>  

<p>
  <m>\displaystyle \frac{$c x + $d}{(x-$a)(x-$b)} = </m><mathInput minWidth="75" name="PF1"/> <m>+</m> <mathInput minWidth="75" name="PF2"/> <answer unorderedCompare><award><when>$PFdecomp = $PFdecompEntered</when></award></answer>
</p>  

<p>
  Once you have a correct partial fraction decomposition, evaluate the original integral accordingly by integrating the two simpler fractions found above.  Fill in the following blanks appropriately to complete your work.  (<alert>Note:</alert> remember that the absolute value signs are necessary in <m>\int \frac{1}{u} \, du = \ln(|u|) + C</m>.)
</p>
<p>
  <m>\displaystyle \int \frac{1}{(x-$a)(x-$b)} \, dx = \int </m><mathInput minWidth="75" disabled>$PF1</mathInput> <m> dx + \int</m> <mathInput minWidth="75" disabled>$PF2</mathInput> <m> dx </m>
</p>
<p>  
    <m> = </m><mathInput minWidth="150" name="Fentered"/> <m>+ \, C \,</m><answer><award><when>$F = $Fentered</when></award></answer>
</p>
